Now once again, if you were to compile You will get 2 errors, sM(int, int, client) and a sM(String, client) are required.
[code]    public static void sM(int event, int part, client pcis){
        pcis.sendMessage(sendMessage[event][part]);
    }
    public static void sM(String str, client pcis){
        pcis.sendMessage(str);
    }[/code]
This demo just lets you send Messages to the client, now the fun part comes.
There is now a new error, we need to add a new array.
This array will just extend the eventID even further. This extension is nothing more than leaching the ID from 1 method to another >_<

This array will be calling to set the arrays within the array. This method will make editing and adding eventIDs easy compared to just starting off from 1 to 500..... The arrays do not need to be in order, also the arrays when you add one to the bottum of the list, it overWrites the aformentioned array if there is already an array on the specific ID.
Also, you are not limited to only DEC numbers, if you really wanted, you could use OCT or HEX >_>
I am staying with DEC....
[code]   public static String[][] sendMessage;
        static{
        sendMessage=new String[][] {
                sendMessage[12855]=new String[] {"You Convert to ancient magic.", "You convert to normal magic."},
                sendMessage[7311]=new String[] {"You are muted and You may not have the privlage to yell."},
                sendMessage[12855]=new String[] {"You Convert to ancient magic.", "You convert to normal magic."},
                sendMessage[12855]=new String[] {"You Convert to ancient magic.", "You convert to normal magic."},
                sendMessage[12855]=new String[] {"You Convert to ancient magic.", "You convert to normal magic."},
                sendMessage[12855]=new String[] {"You Convert to ancient magic.", "You convert to normal magic."},
                sendMessage[0]=new String[] {""}
        };
    }[/code]
The code that I just included will show you that the only code that matters is the one fragment at the bottom and it compiles and works...
Now show in the event Handler (boolean Events) when you call for a sendMessage it will go by the EventID which is also the arrayID concurring to the listed array.

